<HEAD>Archbishop Desmond Tutu Appeals To Harvard to Divest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON> urged fellow
members of a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION> governing board <DATE>Sunday</DATE> to back
divestment in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> until changes promised by that country's
president become reality.
   In a news conference following a closed-door meeting of the
<ORGANIZATION>Board of Overseers</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said that much of what <ORGANIZATION>South African
President F.W. de Klerk</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>last week</DATE> was a declaration of purpose.
   ``Sanctions should remain in place until certain conditions are
met,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said.
   In last week's speech, de Klerk promised to free jailed <ORGANIZATION>African
National Congress</ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON>Nelson Mandela</PERSON> and lift government bans on
30 outlawed opposition groups.
   Tutu, who won the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize for his anti-apartheid
efforts, welcomed the announcement but tempered his response with
pragmatism.
   ``We'd like to see these things immediately but let's be
realistic. The parliamentary session has just begun,'' the Anglican
archbishop said.
   Tutu said he had asked colleagues on the 30-member <ORGANIZATION>Board of
Overseers</ORGANIZATION> to press <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> to withdraw <MONEY>$139 million</MONEY> in investments
in South African companies until <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION> is freed, all exiled
political activists are granted amnesty and the government's policy
of segregation is dismantled.
   The board planned to further consider the divestment issue at a
future meeting.
   The board is less powerful than the university's main governing
body, the <ORGANIZATION>Harvard Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, but is the only alumni-elected panel with
an influence on school policy. The board plays no role in
day-to-day business, but must give formal consent to major
initiaitves and appointments.
   Tutu, who ran for the board on an anti-apartheid slate, was
elected last <DATE>June</DATE> along with <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Labor Secretary <PERSON>Elizabeth Dole</PERSON>
and actor <PERSON>John Lithgow</PERSON>.
   The archbishop said de Klerk's action last week was sparked by
the growing number of countries that had placed sanctions on <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION>, a position <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said seemed to be catching on among fellow
board members.
   He said he was encouraged by the attention <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> had
received in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> amid the historic changes in the
Soviet bloc.
   ``The kind of coverage and response is indicative that, in spite
of what has happened in <LOCATION>Eastern Europe</LOCATION>, which pushed our case to
the back burner, people here do want to see our situation
resolved,'' he said.
   Asked why he was in <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> rather than <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> at
such a critical time, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> replied, ``Harvard is Harvard. The
things that <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> does and does not do have an impact far beyond
what you would expect from an educational institution.''
</TEXT>
