<HEAD>Tutu: Havard Should Divest Until South African Changes Are Made</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON>, who is a member
of <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION>'s governing board, urged the school to
withdraw its money from <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> until promised changes are
made there.
   Tutu told reporters <DATE>Sunday</DATE> that he had asked the 30-member <ORGANIZATION>Board
of Overseers</ORGANIZATION> to sell off <MONEY>$139 million</MONEY> in investments in companies
that do business in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>. The money could be reinvested
once it becomes clear that reforms promised by President <ORGANIZATION>F.W. de
Klerk</ORGANIZATION> will take place, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Board of Overseers</ORGANIZATION>, to which the Anglican archbishop was
elected last <DATE>June</DATE>, had met earlier in the day in a closed session.
The board planned to further consider the divestment issue at a
later meeting.
   Last week, <ORGANIZATION>de Klerk</ORGANIZATION> said he would release jailed <ORGANIZATION>African
National Congress</ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON>Nelson Mandela</PERSON> and lift government bans on
30 outlawed opposition groups.
   Tutu, who won the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize for his anti-apartheid
efforts, praised de Klerk for his announcement, but said actual
advancements would be decided by the <ORGANIZATION>South African Parliament</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We'd like to see these things immediately, but let's be
realistic. The parliamentary session has just begun,'' he said.
``If (de Klerk) is playing games, they would be very odd games and
the world would know how to act.''
   When asked why he was in <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> rather than in <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION> at such a critical time, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said, ``Harvard is Harvard.
The things that <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> does and does not do have an impact far
beyond what you would expect from an educational institution.''
   Tutu ran for the <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> board on an anti-apartheid slate and
was elected last <DATE>June</DATE>, along with <ORGANIZATION>Labor</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Elizabeth Dole</PERSON>
and actor <PERSON>John Lithgow</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
