<HEAD>Archbishop Tutu Urges Iraq, U.S. to Talk, Not Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> should avert war
in the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> by talking out their differences, <ORGANIZATION>South African
Archbishop Desmond Tutu</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Saturday</DATE>.
   ``People must make it more and more clear that we are
peacemongers, because peace is so sensible. It's so much more
sensible than war,'' said the Anglican prelate, who won the <DATE>1984</DATE>
Nobel Peace Prize for his opposition to South African apartheid.
   At a news conference, <ORGANIZATION>Tutu</ORGANIZATION> also urged the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to
continue its economic sanctions against <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> ``until the
process of dismantling apartheid is irreversible.''
   Apartheid is <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s official police of racial
segregation and discrimination against non-whites.
   Although <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s President F.W. de Klerk deserves credit
for some reform, ``the pillars of apartheid still stand firmly in
place,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said.
   Tutu came to this ity of 24,000 people to help raise
scholarship money for South African students abroad and for
American Indian students in <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION>.
   Tutu heads the 2.6 million-member <ORGANIZATION>Anglican Church of Southern
Africa</ORGANIZATION>. This was his only scheduled stop in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION> while en
route to a convocation in <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   The visit was arranged by the <LOCATION>Montana Logging</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Ballet
Company</ORGANIZATION>, a Helena-based quartet that mixes music, comedy and satire
to promote political and social causes.
   Tutu wrote liner notes for the group's latest album after
hearing it perform an anti-apartheid song, ``Take the Barriers
Down,'' in <DATE>1987</DATE>.
</TEXT>
