<HEAD>Bishops To Meet About Government Threat Against Tutu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican bishops from
throughout southern <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> plan an emergency meeting this week to
discuss the threat of government action against <ORGANIZATION>Archbishop Desmond
Tutu</ORGANIZATION>, the church said <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   Tutu, the first black to lead the Anglican Church in <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION>, has been engaged in increasingly bitter confrontations with
the white-led government since <DATE>last month</DATE>, when it banned political
activity by leading black anti-apartheid groups.
   Tutu, winner of the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize for his fight against
apartheid, was briefly detained three weeks ago when he and other
church leaders tried to march to Parliament with a petition
protesting the crackdown on opposition activity.
   He and other clergymen, including the Rev. <PERSON>Allan Boesak</PERSON>,
subsequently vowed to continue challenging the government. Boesak
is president of the <ORGANIZATION>World Alliance of Reformed Churches</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s Anglican bishops, in a statement <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, said the
government has ``launched a carefully planned attack'' on Tutu and
<PERSON>Boesak</PERSON> ``aimed at portraying them as Marxists and isolating them
from their churches as a prelude to state action against them.''
   President <PERSON>P.W. Botha</PERSON> met with Tutu last week and suggested that
the archbishop had aligned himself with the outlawed <ORGANIZATION>African
National Congress</ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement.
   The bishops' meeting on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> is to take place at <LOCATION>Jan Smuts
Airport</LOCATION> outside <LOCATION>Johannesburg</LOCATION>. The Right Rev. <PERSON>Keith Sutton</PERSON>, a bishop
from <LOCATION>Litchfield</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>, is to join African bishops at the meeting
as the representative of the <ORGANIZATION>Archbishop of Canterbury</ORGANIZATION>, the Right
Rev. <PERSON>Robert Runcie</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
