<HEAD>Tutu Denounces Namibian Government as Sham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>KATUTURA</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>South-West Africa</LOCATION> (AP) _ Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON>
preached <DATE>Sunday</DATE> in the territory's largest black township, derided
its multiracial government and renewed his call for independence
from <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   Tutu gave his sermon to about 1,500 people, many in the red,
green and blue colors of the <ORGANIZATION>South-West Africa People's
Organization</ORGANIZATION>, a guerrilla group fighting for independence.
   The congregation had gathered to hear Tutu, the first black
leader of the Anglican church in southern <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>, in a church near
<LOCATION>Windhoek</LOCATION>, capital of the territory commonly known as <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>.
   ``God is here with you in <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>. He suffers with you,'' said
Tutu. ``He says, `It is going to be all right, because I am the God
of justice, I am the God of liberation.'''
   Tutu, winner of the <DATE>1984</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>, lamented last week's
moves by South African President <PERSON>P.W. Botha</PERSON> to broaden power of his
country's chief representative in <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Botha</PERSON> said <PERSON>Administrator-General Louis Pienaar</PERSON> will be empowered
to act against ``subversive'' media, arrange for regional or
racially based elections and refer certain major court rulings to
<LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s appellate court.
   The archbishop spurned the territory's multiracial interim
government as ``echoes of their master's voice.''
   He was joined at the church <DATE>Sunday</DATE> by 18 Anglican bishops who
serve under him. They included the bishop of <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>, who wore a
leopard-skin mitre, and bishops from nearby <LOCATION>Swaziland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Lesotho</LOCATION> and
neighboring <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   Women ululated and held their children above their heads for a
glimpse of Tutu. The service was held at a Roman Catholic church,
the largest place of worship in the township of 60,000 people.
   <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>'s 1.3 million people are <PERCENT>88 percent</PERCENT> black. The rest are
divided about equally between whites, who dominate the economy, and
people of mixed race.
   The rebels in the territory have waged a 22-year-old, largely
ineffectual war of independence.
   On <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, Tutu blamed <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s apartheid system for the
violence.
   Tutu won his Nobel prize for his fight against apartheid, which
establishes a racially segregated society in which <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
   ``We are opposed to all violence, especially the violence of the
evil system of apartheid, however it may be disguised by cosmetic
adjustments,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. ``It can survive only because it
uses evil and immoral methods to defend it.''
   A sheet of hymns distributed at the church <DATE>Sunday</DATE> showed
pictures of detained activists.
   But <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said he opposed violence by both guerrillas and the
military, and he rejected communism as a goal for <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>.
   ``The best defense against communism is a free and contented
people,'' he said. ``<LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> does not want <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION> to be
free.''
   Tutu appealed for <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> to observe a <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> resolution calling
for a South African withdrawal and U.N.-supervised independence
elections in <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>.
   But <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> says it will stay as long as Cuban troops
remain in neighboring <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>, where they are helping the Marxist
government battle combined forces of <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> and a rebel
movement.
</TEXT>
