<HEAD>Bishop Tutu Heads Anti-Apartheid Slate In Contested Harvard Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON> was among five
anti-apartheid candidates for <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION>'s governing board
awaiting word on whether alumni supported their stand against the
school's investments in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   ``It has been a vituperative campaign. Things have heated up,''
said <PERSON>Robert Wolff</PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION>Harvard-Radcliffe Alumnae Against
Apartheid</ORGANIZATION>.
   The group, which has three members on the 30-member <ORGANIZATION>Board of
Overseers</ORGANIZATION>, ran five candidates against a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard Alumni
Association-backed</ORGANIZATION> slate of 10, including <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Transportation
Secretary <PERSON>Elizabeth Dole</PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION>Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Paul
Kirk</PERSON> and actor <PERSON>John Lithgow</PERSON>.
   Results of the election, which was open to all <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> degree
holders and conducted by mail, will be made public <DATE>Thursday</DATE> at
<ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION>'s commencement.
   The anti-apartheid group has pressured the university to
withdraw its <MONEY>$162.8 million</MONEY> in investments in companies doing
business in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   Tutu, a black leader of the Anglican church in southern <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>
and a <DATE>1984</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize-winner</ORGANIZATION>, has threatened to return the
honorary degree <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> gave him in <DATE>1979</DATE> unless the university
backs away from its South Africa-related holdings.
   <PERSON>Wolff</PERSON>, a professor of philosophy at the <ORGANIZATION>University of
Massachusetts</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Amherst</LOCATION>, charged that <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> had campaigned
against the anti-apartheid slate.
   <PERSON>Fred Glimp</PERSON>, vice president of alumni affairs, denied that but
said voters should be wary of one-issue candidates.
</TEXT>
