<HEAD>Illinois Senator Visits Soweto, Meets Tutu</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Simon meeting Bishop Desmond Tutu,
edits to conform, raises identification of Simon as key subcommitte
chairman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. <PERSON>Paul Simon</PERSON> visited black
squatters <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Soweto</LOCATION>, met with <PERSON>Archbishop Desmond Tutu</PERSON> and
renewed his clemency appeal for the <ORGANIZATION>Sharpeville Six</ORGANIZATION>, a group of
blacks facing execution.
   The Illinois Democrat, on a five-day trip to <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>,
conferred briefly with <PERSON>Prakash Diar</PERSON>, lawyer for the <LOCATION>Sharpeville</LOCATION>
Six. The five men and one woman have been sentenced to hang for
involvement in a mob that killed a black town councilor in <DATE>1984</DATE> in
<LOCATION>Sharpeville</LOCATION>, a township south of <LOCATION>Johannesburg</LOCATION>.
   Later, <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> spent about 30 minutes with <ORGANIZATION>Tutu</ORGANIZATION>, leader of the
Anglican church in southern <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and winner of the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel
Peace Prize for his campaign against <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s apartheid
system of race segregation.
   Speaking to reporters after the meeting, <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> predicted that
<ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> will toughen sanctions against <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>. As chairman
of the <ORGANIZATION>Senate Foreign Relations</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on African affairs,
<PERSON>Simon</PERSON> will have a major role in that decision.
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> ``would be eager to avoid sanctions if we got a good
strong clear signal from the government here that they were going
to do away with apartheid,'' <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> said. ``But I'm not getting that
signal.''
   He contends that sanctions could push the white authorities
toward reform.
   Before meeting Tutu, <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> toured <LOCATION>Soweto</LOCATION>, the black township of
2.5 million people outside <LOCATION>Johannesburg</LOCATION>. He also visited two
squatter camps and an all-male hostel for migrant workers.
   ``I've just spoken with a man with five children who sees his
family only once a year,'' <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> said after emerging from the
hostel. ``This is an illustration of what happens under a system of
injustice based on racial separation.''
   Simon also met with <PERSON>Albertina Sisulu</PERSON>, a prominent anti-apartheid
activist whose husband, <PERSON>Walter</PERSON>, is serving life in prison with
fellow <ORGANIZATION>African National Congress</ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON>Nelson Mandela</PERSON>.
   Simon is leading a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> campaign seeking clemency for the
<LOCATION>Sharpeville</LOCATION> Six, whose case has drawn worldwide attention.
President <PERSON>P.W. Botha</PERSON> has refused to intervene. They were granted a
reprieve in <DATE>March</DATE> hours before they were to be executed.
   Diar will argue the case before the <ORGANIZATION>Appeal Court</ORGANIZATION> next month.
   His clients did not physically contribute to the death of the
councilor, according to court testimony. They were convicted under
the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds them responsible
for being an active part of the mob that carried out the killing.
   ``There is a feeling that the system has not provided justice
for a great many people, and to some extent the <LOCATION>Sharpeville</LOCATION> Six are
a symbol of that,'' <PERSON>Simon</PERSON> said.
   He said his request to visit with the <LOCATION>Sharpeville</LOCATION> Six was turned
down but he planned to mention the case in a scheduled meeting
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> with Foreign Minister <PERSON>Roelof F. Botha</PERSON>.
</TEXT>
