<HEAD>Tutu Says West Should Sever South Africa Diplomatic Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON> said
today he would try to persuade Western governments to break all
diplomatic ties with <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> until it eased restrictions on
anti-apartheid groups.
   ``We want to tell the South African government that they do not
deserve to be part of a decent society,'' he said at a news
conference.
   Tutu said Western nations should cut any diplomatic links with
<LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> and expel South African diplomats from their countries.
   ``<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> have kept saying that
sanctions hurt blacks and sanctions are not effective,'' he said.
``While not withdrawing my support for economic sanctions, I am
saying to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> and other Western countries, `Here
is your chance.'''
   Tutu was in the Kenyan capital for a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>All-African
Conference of Churches</ORGANIZATION>, which he heads.
   He said he has called in the past for Western governments to
break relations with <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION>. But he said this time he intended to
actively campaign for such a move.
   ``My own intention now is to challenge the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> to break off
diplomatic relations with <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, to expel South African
diplomats from their countries until certain conditions are met,''
the churchman said.
   Those conditions are a lifting of the state of emergency,
reversal of a <DATE>Feb. 25</DATE> ruling that outlawed political activity by 18
opposition groups, and the release of political detainees,
especially children.
   Tutu, winner of the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize, and other churchmen
were arrested <DATE>Monday</DATE> when they attempted to march on the <LOCATION>South
African Parliament</LOCATION> at <LOCATION>Cape Town</LOCATION> to protest the crackdown on black
opposition groups.
   The Rev. <PERSON>Allan Boesak</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>World Alliance of
Reformed Churches</ORGANIZATION>, also was arrested. In an interview with ``CBS
This Morning'' from <LOCATION>Harare</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Zimbabwe</LOCATION>, he said it is clear that the
government now is outlawing ``all legitimate peaceful activity,''
and that apartheid opponents have no choice but to resist.
   ``And if that means confrontation, if that means disobedience to
your unjust laws then I think that is exactly what we mean,'' he
said. ``We are talking about the possibility of civil
disobedience.''
   He said non-violent protests have ended in deaths in the past
but won't be a deterrent to civil disobedience.
   ``We will have to take the risks that go with it and we will
have to take the consequences that follow these actions of ours,''
he said.
</TEXT>
