<HEAD>Tutu Says South African Blacks Prefer Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE> that
black <LOCATION>South Africans</LOCATION> would be disappointed by a Republican victory
in next week's presidential election.
   ``We would rather see a Democrat in the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> than a
Republican,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said. ``We have suffered a great deal from the
<PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration's policy of constructive engagement.''
   Tutu, leader of the <ORGANIZATION>Anglican Church</ORGANIZATION> in southern <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and winner
of the <DATE>1984</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>, made the comments in <LOCATION>Nairobi</LOCATION> while
attending the annual conference of the <ORGANIZATION>All-Africa Council of
Churches</ORGANIZATION>.
   He is council president and chairman.
   Tutu did not mention either Democrat <PERSON>Michael Dukakis</PERSON> or
Republican <PERSON>George Bush</PERSON> by name. He also did not single out policies
advocated by either candidate that would be harmful or helpful to
blacks in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.
   The <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration preferred a policy on <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> that
became known as constructive engagement _ dialogue with the
white-led <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> government rather than the diplomatic and
economic confrontational tactics pursued by former Democratic
President <PERSON>Jimmy Carter</PERSON>.
   Tutu said President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s policy had failed.
   ``We are now virtually being ruled by martial law,'' he said.
   The archbishop said South African authorities had declared a
state of emergency three times during <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s tenure at the <ORGANIZATION>White
House</ORGANIZATION>. During that period, he said, more than 2,000 people were
killed, many by security forces.
   Tutu is a key activist against apartheid, the policy of racial
segregation under which <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
