<HEAD>Bishop Calls On Wiesel To Join Him In Mediating Palestinian Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lede to CORRECT title to archbishop, sted bishop. Subs
2nd graf to CORRECT typo in name of synagogue. Inserts in 4th graf, `He
said ...,' that Wiesel was not at ceremony.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON>, who won the <DATE>1984</DATE> Nobel
Peace Prize for his struggle against apartheid in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, has
called on a fellow Nobel laureate to join him in mediating the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
   Tutu made the offer to <DATE>1986</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize recipient <PERSON>Elie
Wiesel</PERSON> as he accepted an award <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> from the <ORGANIZATION>Stephen Wise
Free Synagogue</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>.
   ``The idea, I must say, did not come to me `cerebrally,' but in a
vision, because of its symbolic significance, as two men who have
been honored with the Nobel Peace Prize,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said at the award
ceremony.
   He said he had not consulted with <PERSON>Wiesel</PERSON>, the author and
Holocaust survivor, before making his proposal. Wiesel was not in
the audience.
   Tutu said he supported <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>'s right to territorial integrity
and condemned terrorism, ``But <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION> is not infallible,
mercifully.''
   Tutu was honored by the synagogue ``for his leadership in the
struggle against apartheid and for the entire spectrum of civil and
human rights for all peoples.''
</TEXT>
