<HEAD>Tutu Says Western Countries Could End Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Desmond Tutu</PERSON>, the Anglican archbishop
of <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, said <DATE>Sunday</DATE> his country's racial policies would
change immediately if the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and other Western nations
demanded it.
   Tutu, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in <DATE>1984</DATE> for his active
opposition to <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s segregation policies known as
apartheid, said his nation's racial policies are maintained because
of ``immense economic interests'' by Western governments.
   ``If the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the Western countries wanted,
apartheid would end tomorrow,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said at a news conference.
   ``Some actions taken by the Western government have a background
of racism,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> told reporters. ``They say that dollars are more
important than people, especially when those people are black.''
   Tutu and six other Anglican officials arrived in <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
from <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>, where they toured the country for five days. They
leave <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   In <LOCATION>Managua</LOCATION> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, the clerics issued a statement backing the
leftist Sandinista government's recent reforms and called on the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government to help resettle the 11,000 Nicaraguan rebels in
<LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   An agreement signed <DATE>Feb. 14</DATE> by five Central American presidents
sought to disband the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras. The
Contras have been supported by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government since <DATE>1981</DATE>.
   The Anglican officials are visiting at the invitation of the Rev.
<PERSON>Sturdie Downs</PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Episcopal Church</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Edmond Browning</PERSON>, Anglican primate in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, said he
accepted the invitation after hearing about ``the horrible pain and
suffering of the people in these countries.''
   The religious leaders were scheduled to meet <DATE>Monday</DATE> with Gen.
<PERSON>Manuel Antonio Noriega</PERSON>, head of the nation's security forces.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government imposed sanctions against <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> in <DATE>April
1988</DATE> to force the fall of <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON>, the country's de facto ruler. A
court in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> has indicted <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON> on charges of drug trafficking.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> sanctions have seriously damaged <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION>'s economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
