<FIRST>r a AM-Tutu-Emory     05-16 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tutu-Emory,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Tutu Calls For Increased U.S. Pressure To End Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu of <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>
renewed his call for increased <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> pressure to end apartheid in
his country.
   ``What must still happen?'' to prompt the American government to
act, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> asked repeatedly in a commencement address at <ORGANIZATION>Emory
University</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``All the things you hold dear in this land are undermined,
destroyed, held in small account (in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>),'' he told the
graduates.
   Tutu dismissed arguments that economic sanctions against <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION> only hurt black <LOCATION>South Africans</LOCATION>, questioning the motives of
``those who suddenly decide they feel sorry for black people.''
   Tutu further criticized <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> news coverage of <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>,
especially since the government there moved to limit coverage of
protests.
   ``Media in this land, with a few notable exceptions, have shown
extraordinary timidity,'' <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said. He said American readers do
not see the newspaper stories which appear in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>
detailing the injustices of apartheid.
   Tutu also made an apparent reference to a controversy at <ORGANIZATION>Emory</ORGANIZATION>
over the dismissal <DATE>last fall</DATE> of a black professor who was denied
tenure. Supporters of the teacher, <PERSON>Sondra O'Neal</PERSON>, demonstrated on
the campus <DATE>Sunday</DATE> and distributed fliers <DATE>Monday</DATE> protesting alleged
racism at the school.
   Tutu said <ORGANIZATION>Emory</ORGANIZATION> ``has a good record'' of seeking racial justice
in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and around the world.
   ``One would want to be equally concerned about similar issues
here,'' he added. ``... It is critical for this institution, with
which I am honored to be associated, to show a zeal to eradicate
something which could be a stumbling block.''
   Tutu, winner of the <DATE>1984</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>, received an honorary
doctor of divinity degree during the commencement program.
</TEXT>
