<HEAD>Black Archbishop Tutu Meets Noriega In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu of <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION> met Gen. <PERSON>Manuel Antonio Noriega</PERSON> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> and said he asked
<PERSON>Noriega</PERSON> if he would guarantee freedom of the press, free elections
and human rights in <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION>.
   Tutu indicated that <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON> responded positively to the requests
made by him and his delegation of Anglican leaders, but <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> did not
answer reporters' questions about <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON>'s answers.
   As chief of <ORGANIZATION>Defense Forces</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON> is <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION>'s de facto leader.
He was not available to speak with reporters after the one-hour
private meeting.
   Tutu, the black prelate who won the Nobel Peace Prize in <DATE>1984</DATE> for
his efforts against <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s racial segregation policies,
spoke briefly with reporters.
   <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> has elections scheduled for <DATE>May 7</DATE> to elect a new president
and two vice presidents. Panamanians also will elect all 67 members
of the <ORGANIZATION>National Assembly</ORGANIZATION> and 510 municipal officials.
   Noriega is not a candiate for president.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government imposed sanctions against <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> last year,
throwing this country's economy into serious disarray, in an effort
to force <PERSON>Noriega</PERSON> to quit as military chief after a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> grand jury
indicted him on drug trafficking and money laundering charges.
Noriega denied the charges.
   Tutu and his fellow Anglican leaders visited <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION> for five
days before arriving in <LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. Tutu returns to <LOCATION>South
Africa</LOCATION> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
