<HEAD>Some ANC Leaders Willing to Meet With Baker in South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu and
some <ORGANIZATION>African National Congress</ORGANIZATION> leaders said <DATE>Sunday</DATE> they will meet
Secretary of State <PERSON>James Baker III</PERSON> when he visits <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> this
week, even though <ORGANIZATION>ANC</ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON>Nelson Mandela</PERSON> criticized the trip.
   ``If the secretary of state wants to see me, of course I'll see
him. But I will not meet him in <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Mandela</PERSON> said
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> after returning from a five-nation tour. During his trip,
he called on foreign governments to cut all diplomatic ties with
the <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> government.
   <PERSON>Baker</PERSON>, who flies to neighboring <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, has invited
<ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION> to a meeting there. Both men will be attending celebrations
of the South African colony's independence. Mandela has indicated
he will accept that invitation.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> official then intends to fly to <LOCATION>Cape Town</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>
to meet with <ORGANIZATION>President F.W. de Klerk</ORGANIZATION> and black leaders.
   ``We do not want any high-profile visits to <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> because
these can result in a lot of confusion,'' <PERSON>Mandela</PERSON> said <DATE>Saturday</DATE>.
``They suggest that President de Klerk has done something positive,
something fundamental which requires the world to review sanctions
and other strategies, which we have invited in order to increase
pressure on <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>.''
   De Klerk freed <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION> last month after he served 27 years in
prison for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white government.
The president also legalized the <ORGANIZATION>ANC</ORGANIZATION> and other anti-apartheid
groups.
   <PERSON>Walter Sisulu</PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION>ANC</ORGANIZATION>'s national executive and a
close friend of <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION>, said <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> he had received an
invitation to meet <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Soweto</LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION>Johannesburg</LOCATION>, but would
be unable to accept it because he will be in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>.
   However, he said <ORGANIZATION>ANC</ORGANIZATION> leaders <PERSON>Govan Mbeki</PERSON> and <PERSON>Raymond Mhlaba</PERSON>, who
were imprisoned with <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION> for plotting to overthrow the
government, will meet with the secretary of state.
   Asked to explain why <ORGANIZATION>ANC</ORGANIZATION> leaders would meet with <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> inside
the country after <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION>'s comments, <PERSON>Sisulu</PERSON> said the issue had not
thoroughly been discussed earlier. In any case, he said, <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION>'s
meetings are considered different from those of the other black
leaders.
   Tutu, the Anglican archbishop of <LOCATION>Cape Town</LOCATION> who won the <DATE>1984</DATE>
<ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>, said he expected to meet <PERSON>Baker</PERSON>, probably in <LOCATION>Cape
Town</LOCATION>, although the meeting hadn't been confirmed.
   Regarding <ORGANIZATION>Mandela</ORGANIZATION>'s statement, <PERSON>Tutu</PERSON> said: ``I appreciate the
necessity for political leaders to keep foreign governments under
pressure to take a firm stand against apartheid.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
