<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-MotherTeresa     11-15 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Mother Teresa,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Ends South Africa Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother <PERSON>Teresa</PERSON> ended a one-week trip
to <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> today with a visit to a vast black squatter camp,
and a pro-government newspaper praised her for declining to discuss
politics during her stay.
   The 78-year-old nun, winner of the <DATE>1979</DATE> Nobel Peace Prize,
visited an old age home, a church and a high school in <LOCATION>Winterveld</LOCATION>, a
shantytown of 500,000 blacks north of <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> in the nominally
independent black homeland of <LOCATION>Bophuthatswana</LOCATION>.
   At each stop, <ORGANIZATION>Mother Teresa</ORGANIZATION> was welcomed by cheering crowds and
gave brief speeches urging people to love one another.
   At the start of her visit, <PERSON>Mother Teresa</PERSON> told reporters she would
not become involved in political debate and added: ``I did not know
that something like apartheid existed.''
   Under apartheid, <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no say in
national affairs.
   The Citizen, a pro-government <LOCATION>Johannesburg</LOCATION> daily, praised Mother
<PERSON>Teresa</PERSON> for not making political statements and said she was more
worthy of praise than <ORGANIZATION>Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu</ORGANIZATION>, also winner
of the <ORGANIZATION>Nobel Peace Prize</ORGANIZATION>. It described Tutu as a ``political priest
whose pronouncements cause division.''
</TEXT>
